@endnode

@node sort "Unpacking the materials"
In the archive you will find:

o readme.txt - a small text file.

o Several versions of the Clustal V executable:

  clustalv.000 - for Amiga computers with the 68000 processor

  clustalv.030 - accelerated Amiga computers with the 68030 processor

  clustalv.020.FPU - for accelerated Amiga computers with a 68020/030 processor
  plus FPU, or for computers with a 68040 processor. This version is *untested*.

o clustalv.guide - the original Clustal V documentation converted to AmigaGuide

o clustalv_amiga.guide - Amiga specific AmigaGuide documentation (what you are now reading).

o clustalv_help - helpfile for the clustalv executable

o examples.pir - a text file containing the sequences of 6 Pectinesterase
  peptides in PIR format.

o clustalv_sourcecode - a drawer containing the original Clustal V sourcecode and
  documentation in text format


@endnode


@endnode

@node req "Installation & Requirements"

o Any Amiga running Workbench 2 or above. A fast processor is recommended for
  aligning large numbers of sequences. The program appears to require 3Mb of
  FAST RAM for normal operation, more may be required for large alignments.

o Version 41 or above of ixemul.library.

o To run it, double click on the clustalv icon appropriate to your system.
  There are 3 versions of the program included:

  clustalv.000 - for Amiga computers with the 68000 processor

  clustalv.030 - accelerated Amiga computers with the 68030 processor

  clustalv.020.FPU - for accelerated Amiga computers with a 68020/030 processor
  plus FPU, or for computers with a 68040 processor. This version is *untested*.

@endnode

@node use "How to use it"

Double click on the @{i}clustalv@{ui} icon to run the program. Clustal V runs in a shell window,
but is menu driven in interactive mode. The program may be used from the CLI in command
line mode - see the clustalv.guide for details on how to do this.

The program is failry straightforward in operation, refer to the documentation in the
file clustalv.guide for details. An example PIR file containing a number of protein
sequences is included in this archive. To load it into Clustal V, select the option
@{i}Sequence Input From Disc@{ui} (press @{b}1@{ub} followed by @{b}return@{ub}).
Enter the filename as @{i}examples.pir@{ui} and the sequences will be loaded. These
sequences may now be aligned etc. by following the on screen options. Note that the
files output by the program containing the alignments etc. will be in the same working
directory that clustalv is installed in. All the files are output in plain text format,
so can be imported into any text editor/word processor as required. The alignment file
(in this case @{i}examples.aln@{ui}) shows the areas of consensus sequence below the
sequences - areas where all the amino acids are identical are shown by stars below the
area.

@{b}Note:@{ub} Aligning sequences and calculating phylogenetic relationships is very
processor hungry, so be prepared for a lot of waiting. Fortunately, running Clustal V
on the multitasking Amiga enables you to carry out other work at the same time, while
it works away in its own window. :-)

@endnode

@node history "History"

1.07.97 version 0.1 pre-release version.
No problems compiling, seems to work on the Amiga OK.

2.07.97 version 1.0 release version
Wrote Amiga specific documentation, sorted window sizing and execution from icon.

@endnode

@node problems "Known problems"

Closing the Clustalv window without exiting the program isn't a good idea.

@endnode

